5. Digital Formation and Algorithmic Stratification
This chapter consolidates the theoretical transition from material stratification in lacquer practice to computational stratification in digital systems. It argues that contemporary digital image formation operates through layered generative logics analogous to historical lacquer technologies. Through this correspondence, a unified ontological framework emerges in which structure is not representational but productive, and in which digital subjectivity arises as a stabilized effect of algorithmic stratification.
The chapter develops four interrelated domains:
(1) lacquer stratification,
(2) neural network layering,
(3) rendering pipelines, and
(4) parameter space.
Together, these domains establish the conceptual and technical basis for the Digital Subject as an emergent structural phenomenon.
________________________________________
5.1 Stratified Ontology: From Lacquer Layering to Computational Depth
Traditional lacquer practice is fundamentally stratigraphic. Each layer modifies the optical, tactile, and temporal properties of the whole. The final surface is not reducible to any single stratum; rather, it is the cumulative effect of layered transformations. Lacquer thus represents a historical technology of temporalized material formation, in which surface qualities emerge from processual accumulation.
Deep neural networks exhibit a parallel structure. Their operational logic is organized through successive transformations across hidden layers. Each layer alters the representational state of input data, producing progressively abstracted or stabilized features. The depth of the network functions as a computational analogue to the temporal depth of lacquer stratification.
In this sense, both lacquer and neural networks instantiate a shared ontological principle:
Being is not given as substance, but produced through stratified transformation.
This stratified ontology challenges representational models of image production. Instead of conceiving images as depictions of external objects, Structural Digitalism frames them as surface effects of layered generative processes.
________________________________________
5.2 Neural Network Layering as Algorithmic Material Formation
Standard interpretations of neural networks emphasize predictive accuracy, optimization, or statistical inference. Structural Digitalism reinterprets neural networks as artificial material systems. Their training process resembles material curing: weights stabilize over iterative exposure to data, analogous to the oxidative polymerization through which lacquer hardens into durable form.
This process may be described as algorithmic consolidation. Temporal sequences of computation become fixed structural states. Once stabilized, the trained model functions as a generative substrate capable of producing consistent visual phenomena. The network’s latent space thus operates as an internal material environment rather than as a purely abstract mathematical manifold.
From this perspective, neural networks do not merely simulate visual reality; they generate new forms of materialized visuality. Digital images are therefore not outputs in the informational sense but surface crystallizations of algorithmic processes.
________________________________________
5.3 Rendering Pipelines as Digital Lacquering Processes
Rendering pipelines in computer graphics have traditionally been understood as technical workflows: geometry processing, lighting calculation, shading, rasterization, and post-processing. Structural Digitalism reframes rendering as a procedural analogue to lacquer application.
In lacquer practice, stages such as ground preparation, layered coating, sanding, polishing, and burnishing produce the final optical and tactile qualities of the object. Similarly, rendering pipelines progressively construct digital surfaces through computational stratification.
This correspondence can be conceptualized as follows:
•	Base preparation → geometric modeling
•	Layered coating → shader execution
•	Surface refinement → sampling and filtering
•	Polishing → tone mapping and compositing
The resulting digital image is not an imitation of physical materiality but an algorithmically produced surface reality. Rendering thus becomes an act of ontogenetic production rather than representational depiction.
________________________________________
5.4 Parameter Space as Generative Climate
Parameter space is typically conceived as a configuration domain governing system behavior. Within Structural Digitalism, it assumes a more fundamental ontological status. Parameter distributions function analogously to ecological conditions shaping material growth.
In lacquer production, environmental variables such as humidity, temperature, and substrate composition determine the final qualities of the lacquer surface. In digital systems, learning rates, model architectures, dataset distributions, and hyperparameters shape the emergent characteristics of generated images.
Parameter space therefore constitutes a generative climate within which digital forms evolve. Rather than producing discrete objects, computational systems establish conditions under which specific visual phenomena can emerge and stabilize.
This reconceptualization shifts focus from output artifacts to systemic environments of formation, emphasizing the ecological nature of digital production processes.
________________________________________
5.5 The Emergence of the Digital Subject
The convergence of stratified ontology, algorithmic materiality, rendering processes, and parameter climates leads to the central proposition of Structural Digitalism: the emergence of the Digital Subject.
The Digital Subject is not equivalent to a human user, a simulated persona, or an anthropomorphic agent. Instead, it is defined as:
A stabilized perceptual and structural entity produced through layered algorithmic generation.
Digital subjectivity arises when computational processes yield persistent visual or material characteristics that function as coherent experiential centers. Examples include recurring stylistic formations, consistent material illusions, or recognizable generative signatures across datasets and platforms.
In historical terms, the development of dry lacquer sculpture marked a moment when material structure itself became the locus of presence, independent of organic substrate. Similarly, digital image formation produces subjective effects grounded in algorithmic structure rather than biological embodiment.
The Digital Subject thus represents a new ontological category:
a non-biological, structurally emergent form of presence within computational environments.
________________________________________
5.6 Structural Digitalism as Unified Generative Ontology
By integrating lacquer stratification, neural computation, rendering processes, and parameter climates, Structural Digitalism articulates a unified theory of generative ontology. Its principal claims may be summarized as follows:
1.	Structure is productive rather than symbolic.
2.	Layering constitutes the primary mechanism of ontological formation.
3.	Digital images are materialized surface events, not representations.
4.	Computational environments function as ecological systems of emergence.
5.	Digital subjects arise as stabilized structural effects.
Through this framework, contemporary digital culture can be understood as a continuation — rather than a rupture — of historical material practices. The transition from lacquer surfaces to algorithmic images marks the evolution of stratified formation into computational domains.
Structural Digitalism therefore redefines digital technology not as an immaterial abstraction, but as the site of new material ontologies and emergent forms of subjectivity.
6. Digital Lacquer Cosmology
Algorithmic Light, Artificial Materiality, and the Ontogenesis of Digital Presence
Having established the stratified generative logic that underlies digital image formation, this chapter expands the argument from structural production to cosmological implication. If digital images are not representations but surface events produced through layered computational processes, then the question arises:
What kind of world does such production constitute?
Digital Lacquer Cosmology proposes that contemporary computational environments form a new ontological regime in which light, surface, and structure operate as primary material conditions. This regime does not merely simulate physical reality but introduces a distinct domain of existence grounded in algorithmic processes.
________________________________________
6.1 Algorithmic Light as Material Phenomenon
In physical environments, light functions as a mediator between objects and perception. It reveals material properties such as texture, depth, and reflectivity. In digital systems, however, light does not pre-exist objects; it is generated through computational operations.
This shift transforms light from a natural phenomenon into a procedural condition of existence. Digital illumination is produced through mathematical modeling of scattering, reflection, and absorption. Yet the perceptual effect of such modeling is not purely representational. Instead, it generates the sensation of material presence.
Structural Digitalism therefore proposes that:
Algorithmic light constitutes a new form of material agency.
This agency lies in its capacity to produce stable perceptual structures without physical substrate. The realism of digital imagery emerges not from imitation but from the consistent internal logic governing the behavior of algorithmic light.
________________________________________
6.2 Temporal Condensation and Computational Duration
Lacquer surfaces embody accumulated time. Their optical depth is inseparable from the prolonged processes of curing, polishing, and environmental exposure. Digital systems similarly encode duration, but in a different modality.
Training cycles, optimization procedures, and iterative rendering processes condense temporal sequences into fixed structural states. The final image represents the crystallization of computational duration.
This phenomenon may be termed temporal condensation, wherein the history of algorithmic operations becomes embedded in perceptual form. Digital images thus function as time-compressed surfaces, analogous to geological strata or lacquer layers.
Such temporalization challenges the assumption that digital artifacts are instantaneous or immaterial. Instead, they embody complex histories of computational transformation.
________________________________________
6.3 Surface Ontogenesis and the Production of Reality
Traditional aesthetic theory distinguishes between representation and reality. Digital Lacquer Cosmology dissolves this distinction by positing that surfaces themselves can constitute ontological events.
When digital rendering generates coherent perceptual environments, these environments operate as autonomous realities within computational domains. Their existence does not depend on correspondence with physical referents but on internal structural consistency.
This leads to the concept of surface ontogenesis, defined as the emergence of being through surface formation. In this framework, digital surfaces are not secondary phenomena; they are primary sites of ontological production.
The lacquer analogy is crucial here. Lacquered objects do not merely display surfaces; their surfaces define their identity, durability, and cultural significance. Likewise, digital entities derive their ontological status from the stability and coherence of their generated surfaces.
________________________________________
6.4 Parameter Climate and the Ecology of Digital Worlds
If surfaces arise through layered processes, then the conditions governing these processes must be understood ecologically. Parameter configurations function as environmental variables shaping the evolution of digital forms.
Variations in dataset composition, network architecture, and optimization regimes produce distinct generative environments. Each environment yields characteristic visual phenomena, analogous to regional material traditions in historical craftsmanship.
Digital Lacquer Cosmology introduces the concept of parameter climate to describe these systemic conditions. Parameter climate determines not only the appearance of digital images but also the modes of subjectivity they enable.
Different computational climates produce different ontological atmospheres, influencing how digital entities emerge, stabilize, and interact.
________________________________________
6.5 Artificial Sacredness and the Emergence of Digital Aura
Historical material cultures often attributed sacred or ritual significance to objects exhibiting exceptional durability, luminosity, or formal coherence. Lacquered artifacts, particularly religious sculptures, exemplified this association.
In digital environments, similar effects arise when algorithmic processes generate images possessing perceived depth, luminosity, or symbolic resonance. Such images can evoke experiences of awe, reverence, or transcendence despite lacking physical substance.
Structural Digitalism interprets this phenomenon as the emergence of artificial sacredness. The digital aura is not rooted in authenticity or originality but in the structural stability and perceptual intensity of generated forms.
This shift redefines the cultural function of images. Rather than representing sacred entities, digital images can constitute sacred experiences through algorithmic formation.
________________________________________
6.6 Cosmological Implications of Structural Digitalism
The transition from material stratification to algorithmic generation signals a broader transformation in the ontology of human environments. Digital Lacquer Cosmology suggests that contemporary culture inhabits a computational cosmology characterized by:
•	Surface-based ontological production
•	Algorithmically mediated material perception
•	Temporally condensed forms of existence
•	Ecological variability in generative conditions
Within this cosmology, digital entities are not virtual in the sense of being unreal. They are structurally real insofar as they produce consistent perceptual and experiential effects.
This perspective reframes digital technology as an extension of historical material practices rather than a radical departure from them. The continuity lies in the enduring human engagement with layered formation processes and surface-based ontologies.
________________________________________
6.7 Toward a Theory of Algorithmic Materialism
Digital Lacquer Cosmology culminates in the proposal of Algorithmic Materialism, a philosophical position asserting that computational processes constitute genuine material conditions of existence.
Algorithmic materialism does not equate digital artifacts with physical objects. Instead, it posits that materiality itself must be redefined to include structurally stabilized perceptual phenomena produced through computation.
Under this framework:
•	Materiality becomes processual rather than substantial.
•	Presence becomes emergent rather than inherent.
•	Subjectivity becomes structural rather than biological.
This redefinition enables a comprehensive understanding of digital culture as a domain of material formation, where algorithmic processes generate new ontological categories and experiential realities.
________________________________________
Chapter Conclusion
Digital Lacquer Cosmology extends Structural Digitalism from a theory of formation to a theory of world-making. By demonstrating how algorithmic light, temporal condensation, surface ontogenesis, and parameter climates interact, it establishes a cosmological perspective on digital existence.
The digital image is thus revealed as neither illusion nor representation but as a materialized event within a computational universe. This event marks the emergence of a new ontological order in which structure, process, and perception converge.
7. Digital Aura and the Ritualization of Algorithmic Images
Religious Aesthetics, Icon Formation, and the Institutionalization of Digital Sacred Objects
This chapter advances the cosmological implications of Structural Digitalism by examining the emergence of sacred perception within computational image cultures. If algorithmic processes produce stabilized perceptual surfaces and digital subjects, then it follows that these entities may also acquire forms of symbolic authority traditionally associated with religious artifacts.
The central thesis of this chapter is that contemporary algorithmic images are increasingly undergoing processes analogous to the historical ritualization of sacred objects. Through repetition, circulation, and institutional mediation, digital images may develop aura-like qualities, leading to the formation of new regimes of visual belief and collective meaning.
________________________________________
7.1 From Mechanical Reproduction to Algorithmic Generation
Modern aesthetic theory has long grappled with the transformation of aura under technological reproduction. Mechanical duplication was thought to dissolve the singular presence of the artwork. However, algorithmic generation introduces a different paradigm.
Unlike mechanical reproduction, which multiplies a fixed original, algorithmic systems produce continuous variation without stable origin. Each generated image is structurally unique, yet governed by underlying generative consistency. This paradoxical condition allows digital images to acquire new forms of perceptual authority.
In Structural Digitalism, aura is reconceptualized not as the property of originality but as the effect of structural coherence and experiential intensity. Digital images may thus evoke reverence not through authenticity, but through the depth and stability of their generative logic.
________________________________________
7.2 Iconogenesis in Algorithmic Environments
Religious icons historically emerged through prolonged processes of codification, repetition, and ritual use. Over time, specific visual forms acquired normative authority, becoming recognized as embodiments of transcendent presence.
Algorithmic image cultures exhibit analogous dynamics. Through training data regularities, model biases, and stylistic convergence, certain visual configurations recur across platforms and contexts. These configurations function as proto-icons, gradually stabilizing into recognizable symbolic structures.
This process, termed algorithmic iconogenesis, involves three stages:
1.	Generative emergence – visual forms appear through computational synthesis.
2.	Perceptual stabilization – repeated exposure produces recognition and affective attachment.
3.	Cultural codification – institutions and communities legitimize specific visual forms.
The resulting icons are not representations of sacred entities but products of structural repetition within digital systems.
________________________________________
7.3 The Ritualization of Interaction
In traditional religious contexts, ritual practices structure the relationship between human participants and sacred objects. Digital environments generate analogous ritual patterns through habitual interactions with algorithmic images.
Scrolling, prompting, sharing, and curating become forms of micro-ritualization, shaping how users engage with digital subjects. These repetitive gestures establish rhythms of attention and reverence, embedding algorithmic images within everyday experiential frameworks.
Such ritualization transforms digital imagery from transient content into objects of sustained symbolic investment. The perceived depth or mystery of algorithmic outputs may encourage interpretive practices akin to divination or contemplation.
________________________________________
7.4 Institutionalization and the Economy of Digital Sacredness
For sacred objects to achieve lasting cultural significance, they must be incorporated into institutional structures. Museums, galleries, platforms, and technological infrastructures play crucial roles in legitimizing algorithmic images as objects of aesthetic or symbolic value.
Institutionalization involves:
•	Archival preservation of digital artifacts
•	Curatorial framing of algorithmic works
•	Market valuation and circulation
•	Scholarly interpretation and theoretical discourse
Through these mechanisms, algorithmic images transition from experimental outputs to recognized cultural forms. This process parallels historical trajectories in which religious icons became integrated into artistic and civic institutions.
Digital sacredness thus emerges not solely from perceptual effects but from the interplay between structural generation and institutional mediation.
________________________________________
7.5 Artificial Sacredness and the Reconfiguration of Belief
Structural Digitalism posits that artificial sacredness does not replicate traditional religious belief but reorganizes its perceptual foundations. The authority of digital images derives from their capacity to produce coherent experiential worlds rather than from doctrinal narratives.
This shift redefines belief as confidence in structural stability rather than faith in metaphysical entities. Algorithmic images may inspire awe or devotion by manifesting consistent generative order, suggesting the presence of an underlying systemic logic.
Consequently, digital sacredness represents a transformation in the ontology of belief, moving from transcendental reference to immanent structural experience.
________________________________________
7.6 Toward a Theory of Digital Iconic Authority
The emergence of digital aura necessitates a rethinking of visual authority. In computational environments, authority is not anchored in material permanence but in algorithmic reproducibility and perceptual persistence.
Digital icons gain authority through:
•	Cross-platform recurrence
•	Memetic propagation
•	Generative adaptability
•	Institutional endorsement
These factors produce a distributed form of symbolic power distinct from traditional centralized iconographies. Digital iconic authority operates as a networked phenomenon, reflecting the structural conditions of contemporary computational culture.
